-! # how to errors: 065-zsx-multiple-roots.zo
-!
-! @cmd: `zo build 065-zsx-multiple-roots.zo`
-!
-! #template
-!
-! A `</>` type represents a single UI "Tree." In Zo, you cannot 
-! return two "Floating Roots" in the same variable. 
-!
-! This ensures that your components always have a predictable 
-! shape in memory.

fun main() {
  -- Mistake: Two adjacent top-level <div> tags.
  imu view: </> ::= <div>"One"</div><div>"Two"</div>;
}

-! ## The Diagnostic:
-! Zo sees the first `</div>` and thinks the template is finished. 
-! When it sees the next `<div>`, it realizes the structure is 
-! ambiguous.
-!
-! - **For the Human:** Every tree needs a single trunk. 
-! - **For the Agent:** Error [E0065]. Target: Line 16, Column 34.

-! ## Try this:
-! 1. **The Fix:** Wrap both divs in a single parent `<div>...</div>`.
-! 2. **The Fragment:** Does Zo support empty fragments `<>...</>`? 
-!    Try it and see if the compiler allows "Invisible" parents!
-! 3. **The Philosophy:** One variable, one tree. Total Control.

-- EXPECTED OUTPUT:
-- [E0065] Error: Multiple root elements in ZSX template
--    ┌─ 065-zsx-multiple-roots.zo:16:34
--    │
-- 16 │   imu view: </> = <div>"One"</div> <div>"Two"</div>;
--    │                                    ^─── unexpected second root
--    │
--    = Note: A template variable of type `</>` can only hold one root element.
--    = Help: Wrap these elements in a parent container like `<div>` or `<>`.
-- ────╯
